{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A plugin whose manifest is missing a required field is rejected before any code from that plugin is executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is between manifest validation and module-loading/execution. A unit test of only the validator would miss regressions where the loader still imports the plugin despite validation failure.","test_description":"Create a real plugin folder on disk with an invalid `manifest.json` (missing required field) and an entry module with an observable side effect (e.g., writes a marker file or toggles shared state on evaluation). Run the real loader against the directory. Assert the plugin is reported as rejected and the side effect never occurs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When plugin A declares a dependency on plugin B, plugin B's `onLoad` hook is called before plugin A's.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is a graph-resolution and lifecycle-orchestration interaction across multiple plugins. A single-function unit test would not reliably catch ordering bugs in real loader wiring.","test_description":"Create two real plugin packages in a temp directory: `A` depends on `B`. Each `onLoad` appends its name to a shared in-memory array or temp log file. Run the loader and assert call order is `[B, A]`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.9,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When two plugins each declare a dependency on the other, the loader reports the cycle and loads neither.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Cycle detection must be validated in the real dependency-resolution path and tied to load suppression. Unit-testing only cycle logic could miss a bug where detected cycles are still partially loaded.","test_description":"Create plugins `A` and `B` with mutual dependencies and observable `onLoad` side effects. Run loader. Assert it reports a dependency cycle including `A` and `B`, and assert neither plugin’s `onLoad` executes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.86,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A plugin's `onLoad` hook is only invoked after the plugin's entry module has been imported and executed.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The bug surface is the sequencing between module import/evaluation and lifecycle hook invocation. Mocking import commonly hides this ordering failure; real module execution is needed.","test_description":"Create a plugin whose entry module sets `globalThis.__pluginInitialized = true` at top level, and whose `onLoad` throws if that flag is absent. Run loader and assert `onLoad` succeeds with the flag present (or verify explicit recorded order: `module-eval` before `onLoad`).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When a plugin throws an error during its `onLoad` hook, the loader continues initializing the remaining plugins that do not depend on it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This requires real interaction between dependency graph filtering, error handling, and lifecycle dispatch across multiple plugins. Unit tests of error handling alone can miss continuation/skip logic defects.","test_description":"Create three plugins: `X` (throws in `onLoad`), `Y` (independent), and `Z` (depends on `X`). Run loader. Assert `X` failure is reported, `Y` still loads successfully, and `Z` is skipped/not loaded due to dependency on failed `X`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.91,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
